CS 539: Project Proposal 
X Bot Detector: BotBuster
Cole Bennett, Nathaniel Ince, Sheema Farzin, Kamal Dhital
Introduction
Social media platforms have become one of the primary sources of communication and information sharing. However, the increasing presence of automated accounts, commonly known as social media bots, poses significant challenges, including the spreading of misinformation, spam, fake engagement, and manipulation of public opinion. Detecting these bots has become an important problem in cybersecurity and social network analysis. This project proposes the development of a machine learning-based Social Media Bot Detector web application that can predict whether an account is human-operated or automated using account metadata and behavioral patterns.
Functionality
The X Bot Detector will classify Twitter/X accounts as either bot or human. The system will analyze features such as:
Social features: the number of followers and friends (mutual followers).
Posting features: number of posts, posting frequency, and activity patterns.
Profile Completeness: profile images, account description, and verification status.
The location of the account, if possible.
Engagement statistics and interaction patterns using third-party tools.
Users will be able to input account information or upload a dataset of social media profiles, and the system will output a prediction score indicating the likelihood that an account is a bot and which features led to the conclusion.
Benefits and Motivation
A tool like this is useful because bots can significantly distort real users’ online experiences. Automated accounts are used to promote scams, inflate the popularity of posts, impersonate users, or spread misleading information. These problems raise the need for a way for users, moderators, researchers, and companies to identify suspicious automated activity. The target users of this bot detection tool include platform moderators, cybersecurity analysts, digital marketing agencies, journalists, and everyday users who want to be aware of suspicious accounts. 
Existing Tools
Similar tools already exist. One well-known example is Botometer X (formerly Botometer), a tool developed by Indiana University, which analyzes over 1,000 characteristics of a profile, such as friends, social network, temporal activity, language, and sentiment. Botometer outputs an overall bot score on a scale of 0 to 5, along with several other more specific scores. Another example is Tweetbotornot, an R package that uses machine learning to classify Twitter/X accounts as bots or humans. 
While both tools provide a bot score or probability, neither explains which specific account features drove the classification. Additionally, tweetbotornot does not offer a web application. Users must be familiar with R programming, install the package from CRAN, and write code to use it. This makes Tweetbotornot difficult for non-technical users to use. BotBuster addresses these gaps by providing a simple, open-source web application that not only classifies accounts but also explains exactly which features influenced the classification. Bot detector will be an accessible and educational tool for both technical and non-technical users.
We expect moderate difficulty in building BotBuster. We are still early in our machine learning studies, so we chose to implement our detector for Twitter/X due to the availability of a well-documented dataset, which will make this project manageable for us. The potential challenges are identifying which account features are the main predictors of a bot and integrating an explanation component that highlights the drivers of the classification decision.
Plan and Approach
To build BotBuster, we will use the Cresci Bot Detection Dataset. The dataset is available on Kaggle and contains over 37,000 labeled Twitter/X accounts, which are classified as human or bot. The dataset includes 20 columns with account features such as posting frequency, follower and following counts, account age, and profile characteristics. We will begin by cleaning the data and performing exploratory data analysis using NumPy and pandas libraries. We will use seaborn and Matplotlib for visualizing feature distributions. For modeling, we will use scikit-learn, which provides implementations of Logistic Regression, Random Forest, and XGBoost. For the web application, we will use PyDash to create an interactive dashboard of user activity and suspect accounts.
Demonstration Methodology
We will present quantitative results from our trained model by showing scores obtained from standard cross-validation methods as well as scores when applied to an untested data set. Our results will include accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and a confusion matrix. These metrics will demonstrate how our model performs on accounts it has not seen during training. Additionally, we will compare the performance of our model with that of the previously mentioned models. We do not expect our model to outperform others given the constraints of time and labor, but this will give us an idea of how successful we were in creating a new tool and applying our studies.
